postcontent: The box was made in the mid to late 1800s and has a pair of matching percussion brass antique belgian pistols. It has the initials LAW in pearl in the top. This is a unique and rare and cool set.

title: For Sale/Trade:  RARE WWI German F. L. Selbstlader "Army" Pistol
postcontent:
I am working on funding another project, so I have decided to let go of my most prized pistols. It's a rare WWI German F. L. Selbstlader pistol in 7.65 Browning (.32 acp). There were only about 50,000 of these made and almost all of them were issued to the German Army in WWI. They were made between 1915 and 1918, this one was made about 1916. It is in excellent condition and still has about 85% of it's bluing left. The bore is immaculate with no signs of rust or pitting. The grips are made of horn and are also in excellent condition. There are German nitro proof marks, and a military acceptance marking. It seems to be in good operating condition, although I have not shot it. All numbers match (slide, frame and breech block). This would be a hard pistol to upgrade.

I am asking $400 or best reasonable offer. I would rather sell because I am working on buying something else, but I might consider a trade for a Colt 1903 or something else that strikes my fancy. Located in Clarksville, Indiana.

WARNE Rapid Acquisition Multi-Sight Platform, or RAMP, is a cantilever style scope mounting platform that allows proper scope installation on the popular AR-15 rifle. By design, the AR platform was intended for fixed iron sights and did not offer an acceptable mounting surface for optics. As the weapon system evolved from the military designate M16A1 to the M16A3 and M4, Picatinny mounting systems became standard equipment, however, the rail system found on the A3 and M4 weapon systems still did not allow a variable power optic to be mounted far enough forward with conventional scope mounts.

title: For Sale:  Itacha Model 20 X-Caliber
postcontent: tacha Model 20 X-Caliber. Manufactured in 1988. Although these guns were advertised in the 1989 Itacha catalog as the Model 20 in .22 LR the pistols were never actually sold. This gun should not be confused with the Sterling X-Caliber pistol of Lock port, NY. Itacha manufactured the barrels for Sterling and are so marked. This pistol features a unique firing pin system that detonates both rim fire and center fire cartridges. From information gathered according to S.P. Fjestad, author of the "Blue Book Of Gun Values", only about 300 units were ever produced in 22 LR and that production was ceased due to unsolvable production problems. This gun is marked Itacha and features a 10 inch barrel with contoured Gondola Alves grips and forearm. Among the rarest of the rare single shot pistols ever manufactured the Itacha Model 20 X-Caliber is seldom encountered. In fact, there were far fewer made than the Ruger Hawkeye. A must have for the Itacha collector or collectors of single shot pistols. This pistol is in excellent condition. Bluing is excellent

title: For Sale:  Yugo M48 and German Gew. 88
postcontent:
I have a couple of 8mm Mauser rifles I am considering selling.  First is a Yugo M48 in pristine condition.  I have never fired this rifle.  I bought it several years ago but I used the K98 I had instead and just never got around to testing this one out.  It has a mirror bright bore, two bayonets that both fit perfectly, and it still even has traces of the cosmoline in the bolt.  Wood and metal look great.  The second is a German Gewehr 1888 Commission rifle.  This rifle was produced between 1888 and 1897 so shoot at your own risk.  The Gew. 88 was designed to shoot a .318 round nose projectile in a .321 Groove barrel (so called "7,9x57 J");  In 1905, the Germans upgraded to a Pointed bullet of .323 diameter (7,9x57 JS), for the Gew98 (new rifle).  So you would need to either reload your own ammo or use low weight, low pressure rounds.  Also I believe PPU makes ammo specifically for these rifles.

In addition to the rifles I have about 300 rnds of 8mm ammo, most of which is egyptian(corrosive) that I bought back in the 80's and it was old surplus back then.  

Don't really want to sell but I need some cash for auto repairs.  Asking $700obo.

title: For Sale:  -----Wyatt's Outdoors detachable magazine assembly w/ 3 mags-----
postcontent: Up for grabs is my Wyatt's Outdoors trigger guard and detachable magazine assembly with 3 magazines. This unit is designed to replace a hinged floorplate assembly on Remington 700 short action rifles. Unlike other bottom metal systems this Wyatt trigger guard is as close to a drop in fit that you can get. On my HS Precision and the original injection molded stock it required no inletting, and while the magazines are sold as 5 rounder’s I consistently could fit 6 in there. The magazines will work with any 308 winchester based catridge: 243 win, 7mm-08, 260 rem, 6.5 CM, 338 fed, 358 win and any number of wildcats or improved cartridges based on the 308. I used it for the last two seasons on a 243 winchester and it worked perfectly but I’ve since upgraded to a nice AICS Magazine system so I no longer need it. Normally this system costs $250 brand new and each of the mags sell for around $64 a pop. If you bought all of the stuff I’m throwing in new on Midway it would cost you around $380 (don’t forget the shipping…ouch!) I’ll part with it all for $240 OBO. No low balls and I can mail it to you at your expense. I will consider trades for reloading components (I need 6.5mm match bullets, Accurate 1680, or a progressive/turret press) but it has to be reasonable. Thanks for looking!!
